When synchronisation fails, Crowd currently shows a generic message:

{noformat}
Synchronisation failed (see Crowd server logs for details)
{noformat}

It would be better to include some details of the failure, such as the top-level exception. Some failure reasons are common enough that we could refer directly to support documentation.

Steps to reproduce:

1)	Run server-program “helloworld.exe”;
2)	Run Telnet Client (W+R- next step – enter “telnet” – next step - Push To Enter);
3)	Run Telnet Client (W+R- next step – enter “telnet” – next step - Push To Enter);
4)	Run Telnet Client (W+R- next step – enter “telnet” – next step - Push To Enter);
5)	Run Telnet Client (W+R- next step – enter “telnet” – next step - Push To Enter);
6)	Run Telnet Client (W+R- next step – enter “telnet” – next step - Push To Enter);
7)	In the first telnet write “o 127.0.0.1 4010”;
8)	In the second telnet write “o 127.0.0.1 4010”;
9)	In the third telnet write “o 127.0.0.1 4010”;
10)	In the fourth telnet write “o 127.0.0.1 4010”;
11)	In the fifth telnet write “o 127.0.0.1 4010”;
12)	Push To Enter(first window telnet);
13)	Push To Enter(second window telnet);
14)	Push To Enter(third window telnet);
15)	Push To Enter(fourth window telnet);
16)	Push To Enter(fifth window telnet);
17)	Press any key(in first, second, third, fourth, fifth windows)

Actual Result:
Five users are not connected (connect four users), a fifth member of standby time - connections.

Expected Result:
Five users are connected!

A user with an '@' sign in their username will be given an OpenID identifier of:

{noformat}
http://openid.example.com/users/user@domain
{noformat}

however, they would also be able to use an identifier of:

{noformat}
http://openid.example.com/users/user%40domain
{noformat}

with the '@' sign percent encoded. We should make this resource a permanent redirect to the encoded version to prevent consumers from seeing multiple identifiers for the same user.

The SearchResource (JSON mode) which provides the list of users/groups has changed in 2.6.0 version. Previously, When a client requested a resource, the response used to be of the format: 
{code:javascript|title=response.json|borderStyle=solid}
{
  expand: "user",
  users: [
    {
      link: {
        href: "http://localhost:4990/crowd/rest/usermanagement/1/user?username=admin",
        rel: "self"
      },
      name: "admin"
    }
  ]
}
{code}
With 2.6.0, the response has an extra level of indirection, the response looks like(Note the UserEntity object being introduced):
{code:javascript|title=response.json|borderStyle=solid}
{
  expand: "user",
  users: [
    {
      UserEntity: {
        link: {
          href: "http://localhost:8095/crowd/rest/usermanagement/1/user?username=admin",
          rel: "self"
        },
        name: "admin"
      }
    }
  ]
}
{code}
This will break existing REST clients which use the JSON format endpoint.
